messages.message:
The function `PyCursesWindow_New` simply assigns its `win` argument (which could be NULL) to the Python object. There is no NULL check on `win`. Later, any method that tries to use `wo->win` (e.g., to call libncurses window functions) will dereference a NULL pointer if the window wasn't created successfully.

The correct defensive programming fix is therefore:

1. Add a check at the beginning of `PyCursesWindow_New` for `win == NULL`, set an error, and return NULL immediately.
2. Update all call-sites (including `_curses_initscr_impl`) to check the return and not propagate a bad object.

Let's provide the patch.
Here is the patch. This adds a NULL check at the top of `PyCursesWindow_New`.

```diff
--- a/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
+++ b/Modules/_cursesmodule.c
@@ -668,6 +668,13 @@
 static PyObject *
 PyCursesWindow_New(WINDOW *win, const char *encoding)
 {
+    if (win == NULL) {
+        if (PyCursesError)
+            PyErr_SetString(PyCursesError, catchall_NULL);
+        else
+            PyErr_SetString(PyExc_Exception, catchall_NULL);
+        return NULL;
+    }
     PyCursesWindowObject *wo;

     if (encoding == NULL) {
```

